<article class="main__article ateji first-article">
    <h3 class="article-header-text">What is Ateji?</h3>
    <p class="article-text">
    <b>Ateji</b> (当て字, meaning "assigned" + "character") is a system
    that is functionally the opposite of gikun. It assigns sounds to
    kanji and behaves much like the other two scripts in the Japanese
    language (Katakana & Hiragana).
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
    This was an entire system in and of itself at the dawn of Japanese
    writing, known as <b>man'yogana</b>, and it is not only the origin
    of ateji, but the origin of the aforementioned other two phonetic
    scripts as well. As you can imagine, writing out complicated kanji
    not for words, but for simple letters, quickly became too
    cumbersome, and was thus simplified to produce katakana and
    hiragana.
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
    Because of this history, vestigial remnants of man'yogana remains in
    Japanese, which we now call ateji. Sometimes, neologisms would be
    assigned an ateji instead of a more regular spelling, as well. A
    classic example of this would be 寿司 ("Sushi", spelled with the
    words for "longevity" and "governor")
    </p>
    <p class="article-text">
    There was also a trend before World War II to assign ateji to
    foreign loan words (that weren't Chinese, that is). An example of
    this would be the name of America, spelled 亜米利加, which spells
    out a-me-ri-ka. Because of this word, America is often shorted to
    just 米 (the second kanji in this word) in Japanese, which just
    means "rice". Unless you understand ateji, this is obviously
    non-sensical.
    </p>
